<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-282-403  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 282 403.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  Jan 1989 v40 n1 p24(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Successful project management: a force-field analysis.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nicholas, John M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A survey of management literature identifies management practicesnecessary for successful projects.andP;  The best overall criterion forproject success is when the user, project manager and systemdevelopment group all think their expectations were met orexceeded.andP;  Factors essential for project success are strongparticipant commitment to the project's goals, the concept ofproject planning and control and strong involvement in theproject.andP;  Successful projects have good communication andinformation sharing and exchange, complete and clear definition ofthe project, a plan which relates time, money and performancegoals and a monitoring and feedback system.andP;  Force-field analysis,a method which says forces either work to restrain change or tofacilitate change, can be used to show forces acting on theproject, their strength, where problems exist and where solutionsshould be directed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Project ManagementSurveyManagement StyleLiterature ReviewSystem Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Project-management causes of project success. (chart)Force-field analysis. (chart)Generalized force-field analysis of project performance. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>